'''Polylogism''' is the belief that different groups of people reason in fundamentally different ways (coined from Greek poly=many + logos=[[logic]]).<ref name="Mises glossary">{{cite book |chapterurl=http://mises.org/easier/P.asp |chapter=Glossary, Panphysicalism - Pump-priming |title=Mises Made Easier |year=1974 |author=Percy L. Greaves Jr. |accessdate=2011-01-13}}</ref> The term is attributed to [[Ludwig von Mises]],<ref>{{cite news | author=Perrin, Pierre | year=2005 | title=Hermeneutic economics: Between relativism and progressive polylogism | journal=Quarterly Journal of Austrian Economics | volume=8 | number=3 | pages=21–38 | doi= 10.1007/s12113-005-1032-3}}</ref> who claimed that it described [[Marxism]] and other [[social philosophy|social philosophies]].<ref name="HA 3.1">{{cite book |url=http://mises.org/books/humanaction.pdf |title=Human Action |chapter=Chapter 3, Section 1 |chapterurl=http://mises.org/humanaction/chap3sec1.asp |author=Ludwig von Mises |edition=1996 |pages=72–75}}</ref> In the Misesian sense of the term, a polylogist ascribes different forms of "logic" to different groups, which may include groups based on [[race (classification of human beings)|race]],<ref name="Mises glossary"/><ref name="Moseley 2002">{{cite book |title=A Philosophy of War |author=Alexander Moseley |page=239 |isbn=978-1-892941-94-7 |publisher=Algora Publishing |year=2002}}</ref> [[gender]], [[social class|class]], or [[time period]].

==Types of polylogism==

A polylogist would claim that different groups reason in fundamentally different ways: they use different "logics" for deductive inference. Normative polylogism is the claim that these different logics are equally valid. Descriptive polylogism is an empirical claim about different groups, but a descriptive polylogism need not claim equal validity for different "logics".<ref name="Long 2004">{{cite news |author=Roderick Long|title=Anti-Psychologism in Economics: Wittgenstein and Mises|url=http://praxeology.net/antipsych.pdf}}</ref> That is, a descriptive polylogist may insist on a universally valid deductive logic while claiming as an empirical matter that some groups use other (incorrect) reasoning strategies.

An adherent of polylogism in the Misesian sense would be a normative polylogist.  A normative polylogist might approach an argument by demonstrating how it was correct within a particular logical construct, even if it were incorrect within the logic of the analyst. As Mises noted "this never has been and never can be attempted by anybody."

===Proletarian logic===
{{Original research section|date=June 2018}}
The term 'proletarian logic' is sometimes taken as evidence of polylogism.{{Citation needed|reason=Previously a different wiki was used as a citation|date=June 2018}} This term is usually traced back to [[Joseph Dietzgen]] in his 11th letter on logic.<ref>{{cite news | author=Emmett, Dorothy | year=1928 |title=Joseph Dietzgen: The Philosopher of Proletarian Logic | journal=Journal of Adult Education | volume=3 | pages=26–35}}</ref><ref>The Positive Outcome of Philosophy; Letters on Logic, Especially Democratic Proletarian Logic.</ref> Dietzgen is the now obscure philosophical monist of the 19th century who coined the term 'dialectical materialism' and was praised by communist figures such as [[Karl Marx]] and [[Vladimir Lenin|V. I. Lenin]].<ref>A Dictionary of Marxist thought</ref>  His work has received modern attention primarily from the philosopher [[Bertell Ollman]].  As a monist, Dietzgen insists on a unified treatment of mind and matter. As [[Simon Boxley]] puts it, for Dietzgen "thought is as material an event as any other". This means that logic too has "material" underpinnings.{{explain|date=June 2018}} (But note that Dietzgen's "materialism" was explicitly not a [[physicalism]].)

===Racialist polylogism===
Racialist  polylogism is often identified with  the [[Nazi era]]. {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} It has been proposed that the ferment around Einstein's theory of relativity is an example of racialist polylogism.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} Some of the criticisms of relativity theory were mixed with [[Criticism of relativity theory#Chauvinism and antisemitism|racialist resistance]] that characterized the physics as an embodiment of Jewish ideology. (For example, Nobel Prize winner [[Philipp Lenard]] claimed scientific thought was conditioned by "blood and race", and he accused Werner [[Werner Heisenberg|Heisenberg]] of teaching "[[Jewish physics]]".<ref>{{cite book | title=A history of Nazi Germany: 1919-1945 | author=Joseph W. Bendersky | year=2000 | page=140}}</ref>) However this appears to be an argument [[ad hominem]], not polylogism. Modern examples of supposed racialist polylogism are generally misleading. For example, US Supreme Court [[Sonia Sotomayor|Justice Sotomayor]] has been accused of racialist polylogism for suggesting  that a "wise Latina" might come to different legal conclusions than a white male. Although generally given the interpretation that life experience can influence one's ability to understand the practical implications of a legal argument, some commentators suggested that Sotomayor supported the idea that Latinas have a unique "logic".<ref>{{cite news|author=Rich Lowry |title=How Sotomayor Misspoke|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/227625/how-sotomayor-misspoke/rich-lowry}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Peter Wehner|title=Judge Sotomayor, in Her Own Words|url=http://www.commentarymagazine.com/article/judge-sotomayor-in-her-own-words/}}</ref>

